Mate, entitled "Friends." Laura Jean Cameron provides a lively, thought-provoking introduction. Her epilogue considers why Stopes and Hewitt's friendship was largely forgotten and how its recollection reveals early ecology's revolutionary promise but also its colonial and eugenic entanglements.Weaving accounts not only of the professional worlds the correspondents traversed in Britain, Japan, and Canada, but also of intensely personal, relationships involved in the changing nature of their field, Friend Beloved connects careers and emotional trajectories at a key moment in the women's suffrage movement and the making of modern science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBotanistszGreat BritainvCorrespondence. 0aEcologyxHistory. 0aEntomologistszCanadavCorrespondence. 0aSex educatorszGreat BritainvCorrespondence. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Environmentalists & Naturalists.2bisacsh  aBiography.  anatural history.1 aCameron, Laura Jean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800713540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228007135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228007135/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles